Observation Details: Photos might disturb. Injured bird at north end of lake, in area of the bench with view of the lake. When I first startled it on the ground and then photographed it on a low perch, I couldn't tell anything was wrong. When it flew again and dropped out of sight, something obviously was amiss. I then found it in shallow water near the bank. It flopped around a bit and moved into shallower water closer to bank; twisting its head around and looking up. That is where I left it. Phone message has been left with local wildlife rescue. Ongoing situation.  //  12:00pm. When I returned to the spot to check on the bird, it had moved up onto the bank, but I startled it. It dropped back into the water then fluttered onto the bank again. Left it alone. It is twisting its head around awkwardly.

Tiny hawk killed a White-Winged Dove in our yard! We did not see the dove before we saw the hawk eating it. After 10 minutes a congress of crows was attracted: heard at least 3 crows calling from nearby trees. Soon that was too much for the hawk, who flew off with its prey. Hawk definitely Sharp-Shinned, not Cooper's.  Hawk was the same size as the dove (~12"), had solid gray nape with continuous color from crown to back, and short barred tail with squared tips. Please see photos; particularly, please note the photo where the hawk is bending low over the dove when the crows were calling, as if to hide the prey from the crows.

From inside the house I saw this bird make a strafing run down the length of the backyard juniper hedge. I went outside and spotted the bird perched on the fence on the east side of the yard. I went back into the house to grab my camera and gradually began to approach the bird. It was so intent on potential prey that it allowed me to get within 20’. It stayed on the fence until I was satisfied as far as photos went. It disappeared while I was busy filling the birds feeders. While doing so I heard agitated vocalizations from House Sparrows in the hedge, as well as rustling noises. This was followed by an exodus of HOSP from the hedge. I waited for the SSHA to emerge in pursuit, but I did not see it, so I finished up my feeder filling task. When done, as I walked toward the back door, I saw the SSHA on the ground next to the hedge, standing in a pile of feathers. I was able to observe and photograph the bird from inside the house as it fed for an extended period. The SSHA eventually flew to an oak tree where it continued its meal. I went out to obtain additional photos. When the bird moved to a higher perch I went inside. This was the most prolonged encounter with this species in the yard (where its an annual winter visitor), or anywhere for that matter. It was the most confiding (or distracted/innocent/hungry) individual by far. No bigger than a BLJA, so presumably a male.

I then glanced up and saw a third bird (an adult) sitting in the crab-apple tree watching the other two below it.  This is the first time I've ever seen three in the backyard at the same time. Observation Details: Small gray adult hawk, a little lager than a bluejay and smaller than the resident adult Cooper's hawk, with orange bars on breast, no cap, gray extended from head down neck into back, thin legs, square tail with very narrow white terminal band, and short quick wing beats flying up into tree. First seen eating a bird on the ground in the feeder area. As it was finishing this meal, 2 Goldfinches and a Downy came into eat. After it finished its meal, it stayed on the ground just watching for a little while before launching itself into the air, catching a 2nd bird (Goldfinch) and landing on the lower limb of a maple tree. It stayed on this limb until it consumed its 2nd meal while other birds listed came into feeder area. When finished, it moved into upper limbs of the tree and out of sight.

Bird was being harassed by Blue Jays and having strange interactions with a group of Flickers.  It appeared to consider the Flickers potential prey, but the Flickers allowed the bird quite close and it was not always clear who was chasing whom among the branches.    A first year accipiter that I was unable to ID, but per Willie D'Anna  "there are some characters on this bird that fairly conclusively point to an ID. First are the streaks on the ventral body. They are thick and blobby, especially on the belly. On Cooper's the streaks would be thinning out more than this. Next is the relative length of the tail feathers. Although the outer feathers are shorter, the difference is much less than on a Cooper's. Although a bit more subjective, the head shape appears better for a Sharpy, with a small head and a more central eye location. Also, the head shape on a Cooper's is usually more squarish at the nape. Finally, young Cooper's tend to be more orange-buff on the head and this bird shows no such tone."

Observation Details: After six years of birding a Sharpie finally sat still for a portrait!  My birding partner at first thought she had seen a Blue Jay as we drove by.  We stopped and found this hawk. The far away pic is not cropped, shot with a 400 mm lens from across the road.  Size:  This is a small bird, about the size of large Blue Jay or Mourning Dove.  Body:  Though looking a bit chubby for a Sharpie, it was sort of hunkered down giving it the barrel shape look of a Coopers Hawk.  Color: The nape and back were distinctly the same gray color pattern.  Legs and Feet:  The legs are hidden but the foot showing is thin in comparison to the Coopers.  Tail:  The true length is hidden because of the angle of view but lacks the distinct bold white tip of the Coopers. Flight:  The observed flight was away from us and brief.  The wings were short but wide and the flight pattern was  to flap it's wings a few times then glide, then repeat as it headed for more dense forest. Overall, because of the size and flight characteristics we conclude that this is a Sharp-shinned Hawk.

Observation Details: Flew in to the vicinity of the feeder near Hoback and Hillsdale at ca 1532, ca 1 minute after hearing high-pitched calls from chickadees (mostly BCCH) and seeing the redpolls fly up from the ground into cover. The SSHA landed for less than 1 minute in a Juniperus scopulorum at the edge of the yard. Before it landed, a large HOFI flock had flushed and headed to the N or NE; a smaller group of HOFI followed at about the time that the SSHA landed. The hawk gave chase, one bird was not tight with the flock, and the hawk did amazing aerial braking and apparently caught the bird in midair over Hoback St ca 70 m N of the Juniperus scopulorum; it flew W with the bird in its talons. We flushed it from another J. scopulorum in a backyard W of Hoback St. It flew to a deciduous tree along the alley W of Hoback, where it fed while perched on a large horizontal branch about halfway up in the tree, looking around frequently. At 1654 it flew up to near the top of a deciduous tree (not positive it was the same tree; we were more distant at that point), then flew off to the SW. Rapid, strong wingbeats, rather snappy like MERL. **Note: I suspect the prey was a HOFI based on the circumstances, but am not positive. I got a video of the hawk feeding, and may be able to confirm prey species from this.

This bird aggressively pursued Blue Jays at my feeders for over 30 minutes this morning. Blue Jays, in turn, took the initiative in fearlessly chasing after the hawk time after time to drive him away. Even the Pileated helped out, swooping through the feeding station four times. All kept returning to the oak tree to catch their breath, including the hawk. In between attacks, the Blue Jays were lined up nonchalantly on the big tray feeder. The Pileated had plans to dine on the suet but never felt safe enough. During each attack the hawk was making a hoarse squawking sound. When it returned to the tree, it often nestled close to a vertical branch or tangle of branches, and was very difficult to re-find.

Sharp-shinned Hawk on a brief stopover during migration flight at Bull Mountains observation site.
Observation Details: This observation site is especially good for Sharp-shinned hawks early in the migration period and today was a good example. The winds were not especially strong and the Sharp-shins made good use of terrain, staying low and providing good looks from the ridge-top observation point. One Sharp-shinned landed 40 feet away in a snag, sat for a few moments, then resumed its migration journey.

Observation Details: Sub-adult.  Perched in Oaks, flushed the moment I spotted it.   Photo shows the short wide body, and not the long tubular shape of a Cooper's Hawk.  Body has heavy coarse steaks and some barring, Sub-adult Cooper's has finer streaking on the body.    A shorter squared tail  because the feathers are all the same length. Cooper's would show a longer tail with uneven feather length giving it a rounded look.    I do not see young Sharpies often in Pinellas, mostly adults.    In fact I believe this is only my second photo of  a sub-adult.

Observed hawk land in crabapple tree outside kitchen window with good view of nearby bird feeders .  After watching hawk for several minutes, I scanned backyard for other birds. None were present. Later, a male downy and a pine warbler landed in the same crabapple tree. Both were watched intently by the hawk before they flew away. A chickadee then landed in the crabapple tree also watched by the hawk before it flew away. Thirty-five minutes after the hawk landed, a pine siskin landed in the crabapple tree on a large limb with fewer small branches in the vicinity of the siskin. The siskin immediately caught the hawk’s attention, as the hawk repositioned itself in attack pose. Unaware of the nearby hawk, the siskin flew down toward the feeders. The hawk shot off his perch in pursuit of the siskin. The chase began as both birds swooped toward ground level toward the house. Our view was briefly obscured but the hawk circled toward the neighbors yard. At this point I was unable to determine if the hawk had caught his prey. I then saw the hawk glide through the shrubs in the backyard and perch on a distant stump. He had succeeded in catching his prey. My view was greatly obscured by deciduous shrubs but I was able to see the hawk plucking feathers from his prey. It is now 3 pm. I looked up from telling my story. Low-and-behold, the hawk has returned to the crabapple tree.  Note: This is our first record of a Sharp-shinned Hawk on eBird. A couple years ago I was able to rescue a Sharp-shinned hawk knocked unconscious after flying into our house.  ID details: 1) Hawk about the size of a blue jay; 2) Body shape, triangular, broader at shoulders tapering to legs; 3) Lacks helmet look of a Cooper’s Hawk; 4) Continuation of brown color from back of head, down shoulders and down the back in certain head positions.  A Cooper Hawk generally displays a coloration break at neck; 5) Wide banded striped tail, front view-white and dark stripes, (see photo); back view-dark and tan brown wide stripes (no photo).  Photos by GA.

From inside the house I saw this bird make a strafing run down the length of the backyard juniper hedge. I went outside and spotted the bird perched on the fence on the east side of the yard. I went back into the house to grab my camera and gradually began to approach the bird. It was so intent on potential prey that it allowed me to get within 20’. It stayed on the fence until I was satisfied as far as photos went. It disappeared while I was busy filling the birds feeders. While doing so I heard agitated vocalizations from House Sparrows in the hedge, as well as rustling noises. This was followed by an exodus of HOSP from the hedge. I waited for the SSHA to emerge in pursuit, but I did not see it, so I finished up my feeder filling task. When done, as I walked toward the back door, I saw the SSHA on the ground next to the hedge, standing in a pile of feathers. I was able to observe and photograph the bird from inside the house as it fed for an extended period. The SSHA eventually flew to an oak tree where it continued its meal. I went out to obtain additional photos. When the bird moved to a higher perch I went inside. This was the most prolonged encounter with this species in the yard (where its an annual winter visitor), or anywhere for that matter. It was the most confiding (or distracted/innocent/hungry) individual by far. No bigger than a BLJA, so presumably a male.
Adult perched in a tree above the creek.

First terror at 7:09 from adult SSHA. Unbelievable acrobatics around trees and feeders.  Did not make a catch despite smothering a few DEJUs in the snow.  2nd sighting was a juvenile that was cooperative for photos at about 20yds.  Was able to observe 2nd for about 5 mins.  Very interesting to see how it reacted to certain prey birds.  1 HOFI flew w/in 10 yards and the SSHA tracked it very closely but no attempt.  NOFL flew w/in 3 yds and it was ignored completely by SSHA.  WBNU called w/in 10 yds behind and SSHA turned and tracked closely, but no attempt.  During SSHA roost, feeder birds were scarce but not completely absent.  Particularly the MOCHs took opportunity to visit feeders while the usual melee was absent.  As SSHA eventually flew off, 2 NOFLs made a unique, complex chatter call that I’d not heard before - presumably a warning call.  Once SSHA left the general area, feeder birds began returning <60 seconds and in mass <2 mins. 3rd sighting was adult that caught a DEJU that was feeding below suet block.  Photos shortly after catch.  Can’t know if this is a separate adult than from early morning sighting.  Today is SSHA day!

Media notes: Note the small head and bill, yellow eye, white supercilium, and heavily streaked breast. It also has thin legs. Its tail is also slightly notched.
Observation Details: A small, immature accipiter landed in the north cottonwood tree, causing the birds at the feeding station to instantly fly away. This accipiter had a small, round, brown head with yellow eyes and a white supercilium. It had a small bill with a white throat. Its breast and were white, but heavily streaked with brown. It wings looked grayish, like it was maturing. It had a long tail, which was kind of notched in the center. It had thin, yellow legs and small feet. All in all, it fit the bill for an immature Sharp-shinned Hawk. This is my first confirmed, documented observation!

Observation Details: I spent 45 minutes watching and photographing this bird in my yard while it was perched on a brush pile. There were sparrows and maybe quail hiding in the brush pile.  After about 25 minutes it took off after a bird and was gone for 5 minutes before it returned and again perched for a long period on the brush pile.  After it left the brush pile for good I saw it 3 more times. Once it landed in a tree 25 feed from where I was standing, once it came in fast and low just above the ground in my back yard and once it went to the ground after a bird at the brush pile.   Amazing how it can fly through trees at high speed, which it did twice today so far.  This bird is fearless. it looked at me a few times and flinched a couple of times when it heard my camera shutter but did not care that I was watching it.

Media notes: Sharp-shinned Hawk with California Scrub-Jay, Hurlburt Rd., Benton Co., OR - Jan 28, 2018
Observation Details: Saw a small SSHA land on the road with a CASJ in its talons. I watched (and video-taped) the encounter for 8 minutes, during which time both bird kept screaming at each other; the jay grabbed one of the hawk's legs with its foot and the other in its beak, and the hawk proceeded to pluck feathers from the jay's breast. A few times, the hawk tried to carry the jay off, but it appeared to heavy. Suddenly, the hawk let the jay go and flew up to land on a power line, while the jay escaped into the bushes. I looked up from the camera and saw that a cat had approached the birds and scared the hawk off. It went after the jay into the brush, but reappeared shortly after without a bird, so maybe the jay got away. I never saw any blood on it and couldn't tell how seriously the hawk may have injured it.

Observation Details: We were questioned regarding our identification of this bird as a Sharp-shinned Hawk (SSHA) rather than a Cooper’s Hawk (COHA). The hawk in question was observed for more than two minutes sitting on the wire approximately 30 feet from us. We concluded it was a SSHA for the following reasons though it should be noted that our i.d. is based on several features as observed in the field rather than just focusing on a single characteristic, namely the roundish tail seen in the photo.   This is a juvenile hawk as evidenced by the streaking on the chest and belly. The streaking is broad and teardrop-shaped and remains the same in pattern from the chest to far down on the belly. On a COHA, the steaking would be finer, somewhat denser on the chest and less dense on the upper belly. However, this characteristic is variable and separation of SSHA and COHA should not rely on a single characteristic.   The eye of this hawk is located in the center of a rather rounded head (second photograph) giving the bird an alert look. The eye on a COHA would be closer to the beak, giving the bird a slightly "angry" look, and the head would be more "blocky" in shape. Also, the legs on this hawk appear very thin and spindly and do not seem as robust as would be typical of a COHA.   The tail is curious on this bird as it looks somewhat rounded as would be expected on a COHA but the tail feathers on a COHA usually have a stacked look and broad white tips, though in juvenile COHA the white tips wear off over time. This hawk shows very little white if any on the tips of the tail feathers. One tail feather (on the right) is visibly shorter than the rest which is similar to COHA however the corresponding tail feather on the left is the same length as the other tail feathers suggesting SSHA and that perhaps, for whatever reason, the shorter tail feather has not come in all the way.   Finally, this was a very small hawk. We observed a Blue Jay (BLJA) vigorously scolding the hawk which is why the bird is turned to the right of the frame in the second photograph. Thus, we had a direct size comparison at the time of the observation. This hawk was roughly the same size as the BLJA (approximately 11 inches length). To confirm the size I measured the distance between the two wires based on the point the photograph was taken and was able to confirm that the hawk was approximately 11½ inches in length from the tip of the tail to the top of the head. Therefore, based on all the aforementioned characteristics, including streaking, head-shape, location of the eye, tail characteristics, thin legs and the size, we concluded that this is an immature SSHA.

Observation Details: This is likely the same bird that previously visited our feeders and took a female Cardinal.  This time, we watched as it made an initial dash into the flock of feeding birds but missed its mark.  It sat above our brush pile for plenty of time for photos before going to our large mountain laurel to hunt the 5 Cardinals that had taken refuge there.  The hawk unsuccessfully chased these birds inside the bush for 5 minutes before four of the Cardinals were able to escape.  We last saw the SSHA chasing the remaining female Cardinal to a point we could not observe.

At 1448, I briefly saw a distant raptor with barred black and white tail fly from where it had apparently been perched, high in a tree in the aspen grove. At 1455, I located a SSHA (presumably the same raptor), perched 4/5 of the way up in a dead aspen ca 10 m from the edge of the largest continuous aspen grove. The tree in which it was perched was a few meters taller than average. While I observed it perching here, it moved its head from time to time, looking ahead, left, and right. At 1504, it leaned forward briefly and raised its tail at the same time, then settled back down and fluffed its back feathers. At 1507, it briefly raised its right foot (which was yellow), then turned its head backwards and preened its back briefly. At 1508, without advance warning it bent forward and launched into a glide to the south in the aspen grove, out of sight. At 1512, if flew from this westernmost, large aspen grove to the east, beating its wings and passing by ca 5 perched BBMA, which increased their rate of calling a lot momentarily. It glided to a landing low at the edge of a smaller aspen grove, where I lost sight of it. Within 30 seconds, 4 smallish groups of BOWA flew low overhead from east to west, low over the aspens, ca 100 or more total.  This SSHA had a very interesting appearance, striking me as perhaps intermediate between adult and juvenile. Brownish head, pale eye, yellowish cere and legs; barring on flanks but apparently some streaking as well on its pale underside; lots of pale spotting on the back. Small head, fluffy body; rounded wingtips in flight.

Tiny hawk killed a White-Winged Dove in our yard! We did not see the dove before we saw the hawk eating it. After 10 minutes a congress of crows was attracted: heard at least 3 crows calling from nearby trees. Soon that was too much for the hawk, who flew off with its prey. Hawk definitely Sharp-Shinned, not Cooper's.  Hawk was the same size as the dove (~12"), had solid gray nape with continuous color from crown to back, and short barred tail with squared tips. Please see photos; particularly, please note the photo where the hawk is bending low over the dove when the crows were calling, as if to hide the prey from the crows.

From inside the house I saw this bird make a strafing run down the length of the backyard juniper hedge. I went outside and spotted the bird perched on the fence on the east side of the yard. I went back into the house to grab my camera and gradually began to approach the bird. It was so intent on potential prey that it allowed me to get within 20’. It stayed on the fence until I was satisfied as far as photos went. It disappeared while I was busy filling the birds feeders. While doing so I heard agitated vocalizations from House Sparrows in the hedge, as well as rustling noises. This was followed by an exodus of HOSP from the hedge. I waited for the SSHA to emerge in pursuit, but I did not see it, so I finished up my feeder filling task. When done, as I walked toward the back door, I saw the SSHA on the ground next to the hedge, standing in a pile of feathers. I was able to observe and photograph the bird from inside the house as it fed for an extended period. The SSHA eventually flew to an oak tree where it continued its meal. I went out to obtain additional photos. When the bird moved to a higher perch I went inside. This was the most prolonged encounter with this species in the yard (where its an annual winter visitor), or anywhere for that matter. It was the most confiding (or distracted/innocent/hungry) individual by far. No bigger than a BLJA, so presumably a male.

Small accipiter, heavy brown streaks indicate a juvenile/immature, the heaviness of the streaks points toward Sharp-shinned instead of Cooper's Hawk.  When flying, the tail is squared off, head projection reaches barely past the leading edge of the wing, tail is relatively short, and neck is not well-defined.  Head is narrow when heading directly towards us,  There is a white supercilium that is well-defined.  All these traits, while not definitive for Sharpies, nevertheless point in that direction -- so Sharpie it is, based on a preponderance of the field marks.

A not real easy identification, as the tail tip did look a bit rounded. But both in the field, and especially later, while looking at our photos of the bird (which was circling for a bit over YRP), I felt it was a Sharp-shinned Hawk based on several features.  In life it impressed as a small bird (though of course that not diagnostic in itself), looked small-headed, kept its wings pulled forward slightly, typical of SSHA (which also contributes to the minimal "head projection").  In the images that show enough detail, the underparts depict a juvenile bird (dominated by vertical streaking in the center of the breast but also showing some horizontal barring on the sides/flanks, more typical of SSHA); also the underparts appear somewhat more coarsely pattered, slightly better for SSHA. The white terminal band to the tail seemed fairly narrow, especially for a bird that should still be in relatively fresh plumage (not a whole lot of difference, but I'd think a fresh Cooper's would show a slightly wider white terminal band). And lastly, the tail appeared relatively short to the bird's overall size, for an Accipiter (although this being another feature which can be fairly subjective).

Observation Details: This photo allowed for a careful study of this bird (I'm going with juvenile due to yellow eye and plumage color). In particular a study of the tail, I had thought it might be Cooper's at first, since the outer tail feathers that are visible seemed shorter than the central ones, giving it a somewhat rounded look, BUT, Alvaro helped me to understand the following which makes this a Sharpie!  TAIL: "The shape of Cooper's is more rounded and also longer, so the shorter rectrix is actually not unusual on Sharpie, but having a stack of central rectrices that are very similar in length would be unusual in Cooper's. They usually show the graduation within the central feathers too. As well, usually Cooper's has a broader white terminal band."  EYE/HEAD: "The owl like (pygmy owl look) of big eyes and seemingly smaller head is classic of Sharpie. Cooper's tends to have that flat capped look, and small eyes that are closer up to the bill. They look meaner, while sharpies look surprised. That is the look I see in your photo."  NAPE: "That cinnamon on the nape also looks good for Sharpie."

Although Cooper's Hawks are regular visitors to the bird feeders in my backyard, Sharp-shinned Hawks are decidedly not; I have not observed a Sharp-shinned Hawk at this location in three years.  This unfortunate juvenile was being mobbed by several crows and flew into a sliding glass door.  It was briefly stunned, then attempted to leave, but the crows continued to harass it.  It took shelter in a planter (the English boxwood in the photographs are about 10 inches high for scale), rested for a few minutes, then flew away (apparently none the worse for the wear) after the crows lost interest.

A small bodied accipiter with a heavily streaked chest  and a barred square and white-tipped tail distinctively seen in a series of photos as it dispatched a BLJA. 22F NW winds, blue skies.  I saw many BLJA initially so I stopped at the Young's Mountain Road. The AMCR were on the ground when I realized there was a Sharp-shinned Hawk and it had just captured a BLJA. The struggle to dispatch the BAJA took about 8 to 10 minutes which I tried to capture below. The BLJA was fighting valiantly and was calling loudly initially. There was a mobbing of sorts going on initially which included some BLJA and AMCR. I changed position but kept a good distance away capturing unique moments. Finally the BLJA stopped fighting and the SSHA flew off just as I looked away briefly, it was gone. As I think about the entire event, the BLJA feathers flying on the wind is always the most stunning moment in the struggle. The SSHA dispatched the BLJA by going for its heart or disembowelment.

Observed hawk land in crabapple tree outside kitchen window with good view of nearby bird feeders .  After watching hawk for several minutes, I scanned backyard for other birds. None were present. Later, a male downy and a pine warbler landed in the same crabapple tree. Both were watched intently by the hawk before they flew away. A chickadee then landed in the crabapple tree also watched by the hawk before it flew away. Thirty-five minutes after the hawk landed, a pine siskin landed in the crabapple tree on a large limb with fewer small branches in the vicinity of the siskin. The siskin immediately caught the hawk’s attention, as the hawk repositioned itself in attack pose. Unaware of the nearby hawk, the siskin flew down toward the feeders. The hawk shot off his perch in pursuit of the siskin. The chase began as both birds swooped toward ground level toward the house. Our view was briefly obscured but the hawk circled toward the neighbors yard. At this point I was unable to determine if the hawk had caught his prey. I then saw the hawk glide through the shrubs in the backyard and perch on a distant stump. He had succeeded in catching his prey. My view was greatly obscured by deciduous shrubs but I was able to see the hawk plucking feathers from his prey. It is now 3 pm. I looked up from telling my story. Low-and-behold, the hawk has returned to the crabapple tree.  Note: This is our first record of a Sharp-shinned Hawk on eBird. A couple years ago I was able to rescue a Sharp-shinned hawk knocked unconscious after flying into our house.  ID details: 1) Hawk about the size of a blue jay; 2) Body shape, triangular, broader at shoulders tapering to legs; 3) Lacks helmet look of a Cooper’s Hawk; 4) Continuation of brown color from back of head, down shoulders and down the back in certain head positions.  A Cooper Hawk generally displays a coloration break at neck; 5) Wide banded striped tail, front view-white and dark stripes, (see photo); back view-dark and tan brown wide stripes (no photo).  Photos by GA.

Tiny hawk killed a White-Winged Dove in our yard! We did not see the dove before we saw the hawk eating it. After 10 minutes a congress of crows was attracted: heard at least 3 crows calling from nearby trees. Soon that was too much for the hawk, who flew off with its prey. Hawk definitely Sharp-Shinned, not Cooper's.  Hawk was the same size as the dove (~12"), had solid gray nape with continuous color from crown to back, and short barred tail with squared tips. Please see photos; particularly, please note the photo where the hawk is bending low over the dove when the crows were calling, as if to hide the prey from the crows.

Locality: Riparian Preserve at Gilbert Water Ranch

Observation Details: From inside the house I saw this bird make a strafing run down the length of the backyard juniper hedge. I went outside and spotted the bird perched on the fence on the east side of the yard. I went back into the house to grab my camera and gradually began to approach the bird. It was so intent on potential prey that it allowed me to get within 20’. It stayed on the fence until I was satisfied as far as photos went. It disappeared while I was busy filling the birds feeders. While doing so I heard agitated vocalizations from House Sparrows in the hedge, as well as rustling noises. This was followed by an exodus of HOSP from the hedge. I waited for the SSHA to emerge in pursuit, but I did not see it, so I finished up my feeder filling task. When done, as I walked toward the back door, I saw the SSHA on the ground next to the hedge, standing in a pile of feathers. I was able to observe and photograph the bird from inside the house as it fed for an extended period. The SSHA eventually flew to an oak tree where it continued its meal. I went out to obtain additional photos. When the bird moved to a higher perch I went inside. This was the most prolonged encounter with this species in the yard (where its an annual winter visitor), or anywhere for that matter. It was the most confiding (or distracted/innocent/hungry) individual by far. No bigger than a BLJA, so presumably a male.
Pics

First terror at 7:09 from adult SSHA. Unbelievable acrobatics around trees and feeders.  Did not make a catch despite smothering a few DEJUs in the snow.  2nd sighting was a juvenile that was cooperative for photos at about 20yds.  Was able to observe 2nd for about 5 mins.  Very interesting to see how it reacted to certain prey birds.  1 HOFI flew w/in 10 yards and the SSHA tracked it very closely but no attempt.  NOFL flew w/in 3 yds and it was ignored completely by SSHA.  WBNU called w/in 10 yds behind and SSHA turned and tracked closely, but no attempt.  During SSHA roost, feeder birds were scarce but not completely absent.  Particularly the MOCHs took opportunity to visit feeders while the usual melee was absent.  As SSHA eventually flew off, 2 NOFLs made a unique, complex chatter call that I’d not heard before - presumably a warning call.  Once SSHA left the general area, feeder birds began returning <60 seconds and in mass <2 mins. 3rd sighting was adult that caught a DEJU that was feeding below suet block.  Photos shortly after catch.  Can’t know if this is a separate adult than from early morning sighting.  Today is SSHA day!

This bird aggressively pursued Blue Jays at my feeders for over 30 minutes this morning. Blue Jays, in turn, took the initiative in fearlessly chasing after the hawk time after time to drive him away. Even the Pileated helped out, swooping through the feeding station four times. All kept returning to the oak tree to catch their breath, including the hawk. In between attacks, the Blue Jays were lined up nonchalantly on the big tray feeder. The Pileated had plans to dine on the suet but never felt safe enough. During each attack the hawk was making a hoarse squawking sound. When it returned to the tree, it often nestled close to a vertical branch or tangle of branches, and was very difficult to re-find.

Observation Details: photos D094987-D095015 -- ID'd by Tony Leukering who listed the following points: — Large eye relative to small head, with eye fairly centered on face — Crown not contrastingly black — Nape concolorous with crown — Skinny legs and toes — Outermost rectrix (r6) virtually same length as r5 — r6 (the left one seen well enough, barely, only on the under-side-of-tail pic) with distinct, fairly sharp outer corner with the very apex of feather at feather shaft or on outer web (the apex of this feather on Coop is at shaft or inner web and with the outer corner noticeably rounded, accentuating the rounded corner of tail created by graduated rectrices)  To me, this hawk visually seemed hooded at the time, but somewhat capped in some photos (lighting was bad in the tree); visually not crested, but slightly crested? in some photos; "big" orange eye ("bug-eyed"?) - not "smaller" like a Coop's relative to the face; most tail feathers, especially outer ones, same length with very little white on the tips; tail flat-tipped (straight across), not overall rounded; overall GIS seemed "large" (but it was close to the window); significantly larger than the Blue Jay-sized male Sharpie that took a Downy a few days ago; my initial ID was a female SSHA, adult (or subadult?), otherwise a male COHA based on underside barring... It was plucking and eating a small bird in the big Norway spruce on the north side of our house.

A not real easy identification, as the tail tip did look a bit rounded. But both in the field, and especially later, while looking at our photos of the bird (which was circling for a bit over YRP), I felt it was a Sharp-shinned Hawk based on several features.  In life it impressed as a small bird (though of course that not diagnostic in itself), looked small-headed, kept its wings pulled forward slightly, typical of SSHA (which also contributes to the minimal "head projection").  In the images that show enough detail, the underparts depict a juvenile bird (dominated by vertical streaking in the center of the breast but also showing some horizontal barring on the sides/flanks, more typical of SSHA); also the underparts appear somewhat more coarsely pattered, slightly better for SSHA. The white terminal band to the tail seemed fairly narrow, especially for a bird that should still be in relatively fresh plumage (not a whole lot of difference, but I'd think a fresh Cooper's would show a slightly wider white terminal band). And lastly, the tail appeared relatively short to the bird's overall size, for an Accipiter (although this being another feature which can be fairly subjective).

Media notes: Sharp-shinned Hawk with California Scrub-Jay, Hurlburt Rd., Benton Co., OR - Jan 28, 2018
Observation Details: Saw a small SSHA land on the road with a CASJ in its talons. I watched (and video-taped) the encounter for 8 minutes, during which time both bird kept screaming at each other; the jay grabbed one of the hawk's legs with its foot and the other in its beak, and the hawk proceeded to pluck feathers from the jay's breast. A few times, the hawk tried to carry the jay off, but it appeared to heavy. Suddenly, the hawk let the jay go and flew up to land on a power line, while the jay escaped into the bushes. I looked up from the camera and saw that a cat had approached the birds and scared the hawk off. It went after the jay into the brush, but reappeared shortly after without a bird, so maybe the jay got away. I never saw any blood on it and couldn't tell how seriously the hawk may have injured it.

Observation Details: Capture un geai bleu et se laisse choire sous le site de capture. Bien que sous l'emprise parfaite des serres de son agresseur, le geai bleu était fort vigoureux donnant des coups de bec sur la poitrine de l'épervier, les deux oiseaux se faisant face. Le geai bleu gardait la huppe bien dépoyée donnant de bons coups d'ailes à l'épervier qui ont su, à quelques reprises, mettre en déséquilibre le rapace. Cette vigueure de la victime s'est poursuivit durant près de deux minutes et demie. Durant cette période l'épervier plumait le geai qui répondait avec vaillance. Le geai bleue se mit à être moins combatif et il cessa de combattre après quatre minutes alors que les premières traces de sang se voyaient sur la tête de l'épervier, sang provenant de l'ouverture faite au bas-ventre. Le corps de la victime cessa toute réaction aux coups de bec sept minutes après la capture. S'envole avec le geai bleu dans ses serres neuf minutes après la capture.

Observation Details: Observed hawk land in crabapple tree outside kitchen window with good view of nearby bird feeders .  After watching hawk for several minutes, I scanned backyard for other birds. None were present. Later, a male downy and a pine warbler landed in the same crabapple tree. Both were watched intently by the hawk before they flew away. A chickadee then landed in the crabapple tree also watched by the hawk before it flew away. Thirty-five minutes after the hawk landed, a pine siskin landed in the crabapple tree on a large limb with fewer small branches in the vicinity of the siskin. The siskin immediately caught the hawk’s attention, as the hawk repositioned itself in attack pose. Unaware of the nearby hawk, the siskin flew down toward the feeders. The hawk shot off his perch in pursuit of the siskin. The chase began as both birds swooped toward ground level toward the house. Our view was briefly obscured but the hawk circled toward the neighbors yard. At this point I was unable to determine if the hawk had caught his prey. I then saw the hawk glide through the shrubs in the backyard and perch on a distant stump. He had succeeded in catching his prey. My view was greatly obscured by deciduous shrubs but I was able to see the hawk plucking feathers from his prey. It is now 3 pm. I looked up from telling my story. Low-and-behold, the hawk has returned to the crabapple tree.  Note: This is our first record of a Sharp-shinned Hawk on eBird. A couple years ago I was able to rescue a Sharp-shinned hawk knocked unconscious after flying into our house.  ID details: 1) Hawk about the size of a blue jay; 2) Body shape, triangular, broader at shoulders tapering to legs; 3) Lacks helmet look of a Cooper’s Hawk; 4) Continuation of brown color from back of head, down shoulders and down the back in certain head positions.  A Cooper Hawk generally displays a coloration break at neck; 5) Wide banded striped tail, front view-white and dark stripes, (see photo); back view-dark and tan brown wide stripes (no photo).  Photos by GA.

From inside the house I saw this bird make a strafing run down the length of the backyard juniper hedge. I went outside and spotted the bird perched on the fence on the east side of the yard. I went back into the house to grab my camera and gradually began to approach the bird. It was so intent on potential prey that it allowed me to get within 20’. It stayed on the fence until I was satisfied as far as photos went. It disappeared while I was busy filling the birds feeders. While doing so I heard agitated vocalizations from House Sparrows in the hedge, as well as rustling noises. This was followed by an exodus of HOSP from the hedge. I waited for the SSHA to emerge in pursuit, but I did not see it, so I finished up my feeder filling task. When done, as I walked toward the back door, I saw the SSHA on the ground next to the hedge, standing in a pile of feathers. I was able to observe and photograph the bird from inside the house as it fed for an extended period. The SSHA eventually flew to an oak tree where it continued its meal. I went out to obtain additional photos. When the bird moved to a higher perch I went inside. This was the most prolonged encounter with this species in the yard (where its an annual winter visitor), or anywhere for that matter. It was the most confiding (or distracted/innocent/hungry) individual by far. No bigger than a BLJA, so presumably a male.

Locality: Effie Yeaw Nature Center, Carmichael US-CA 38.61721, -121.31192

Observation Details: This bird aggressively pursued Blue Jays at my feeders for over 30 minutes this morning. Blue Jays, in turn, took the initiative in fearlessly chasing after the hawk time after time to drive him away. Even the Pileated helped out, swooping through the feeding station four times. All kept returning to the oak tree to catch their breath, including the hawk. In between attacks, the Blue Jays were lined up nonchalantly on the big tray feeder. The Pileated had plans to dine on the suet but never felt safe enough. During each attack the hawk was making a hoarse squawking sound. When it returned to the tree, it often nestled close to a vertical branch or tangle of branches, and was very difficult to re-find.

Small hawk with relatively short rounded wings. Adults are gray above with pale orange barring below; immatures are browner and streaky. Very similar to Cooper's Hawk, especially in plumage, but smaller overall with smaller head, more squared-off tail, and more petite feet. Also note quicker, snappier wingbeats. Breeds in extensive forests. Feeds mainly on birds captured in flight. Often stalks feeders in search of prey.

Photos might disturb. Injured bird at north end of lake, in area of the bench with view of the lake. When I first startled it on the ground and then photographed it on a low perch, I couldn't tell anything was wrong. When it flew again and dropped out of sight, something obviously was amiss. I then found it in shallow water near the bank. It flopped around a bit and moved into shallower water closer to bank; twisting its head around and looking up. That is where I left it. Phone message has been left with local wildlife rescue. Ongoing situation.  //  12:00pm. When I returned to the spot to check on the bird, it had moved up onto the bank, but I startled it. It dropped back into the water then fluttered onto the bank again. Left it alone. It is twisting its head around awkwardly.

At first mis-identified tentatively as a Cooper's Hawk. The rounded tail, with white directly below the bottom dark bar is visible in the picture. The bird appeared to be too large even for a female Sharp-shinned. On the other hand, my pictures show a rounded head, and Sharp-shinned hawks are more frequent here. My observation was brief and less than satisfactory, as I only had a back view and spent most of the observation time maneuvering along our paths in the snow to get to a place where it's head was not obscured by branches. 2 more pictures which I had considered useless, cropped to show the head and shoulders, show a very dark nape and a brownish wash to the head, which confirm it is a Sharp-shinned, not a Coopers

Mr. Havoc got one of my Downy Woodpeckers today. Looking at the time stamps of my pictures he first arrived on the scene at 2:55 P.M. and left out at 3:46 P.M. with the Downy. I went out on the deck twice to shoo it away for birds to escape. He just wasn't giving up today hanging for almost an hour! Even when he fled it wasn't deep into the woods and I could still see him. Observation Details: had a difficult time with Accipiters today. I saw this pale juvenile looking one pictured below 3 different times, initially called it Sharp-shinned then changed my mine to Cooper's and finally, while taking this picture, I decided it was a Sharpy again. Then a little later the other pale one showed up and circled for a little while. Definitely a different bird, missing a primary on left side and faded but adult looking plumage. Smaller sized than other accipiter, I thought it could be a Merlin for a while. I feel more confident calling this one a Sharpy.

This bird landed in a small maple tree just outside our kitchen door.  At first glance I saw a lot of white next to the wing and I thought it was a white winged dove, then it fluffed itself back together and  I looked up and saw that it was clearly either  a Sharp-shinned or Cooper's hawk.  I got a fairly good picture from a little farther away through a door in the room where my camera was and am pretty sure now that it is a Sharp-shinned, because: It was the size of a white winged dove; Its head is rounded not squared off like the Cooper's, the back of the head is all blue-grey with no lighter colored feathers at the nape.

I checked out the feeder window after hearing a thump that was a little louder than what I have been hearing from a male cardinal hitting it. The branch the hawk is sitting on is 1" in diameter. I checked in order to double check the bird's size which I felt was under 12". So, hunched like this, it is about 10" from tail tip to head. I'd already decided it was a Sharp-shinned based on the small head, angle of the forehead (not sloping), and the light tips on the tail feathers that weren't as broad as I'd expect for a Cooper's. I was able to get several photos. No other birds were anywhere near the feeders, but 3 grackles in the trees next door flew off when the hawk flew from my feeder tree, swooped low under some pines and upward out of view into the other yard.
Originally misidentified as a Cooper's Hawk, this Sharp-shinned Hawk had caught what appeared to be a European Starling in my backyard near the feeders.

Observation Details: All high and moving with a southerly component.  Juvenile showing not only Sharpie traits but juvenile traits too, such as longer proportioned tail and notch that is often more prominent in juvies and the "S" curve in the trailing edge is classic, often exaggerated more in juvies.

The golf cart path went directly under this branch, and I stopped to take a quick closeup; this very tiny hawk was less than 8 feet above me. The bird was so small, my partner said I shouldn’t bother – “it is just a dove”, because it’s back was to us as we drove up. It was hunched over with it’s feathers a bit fluffed out for a few moments. I almost didn’t stop. I took many photos, and it didn’t seem to mind me being so close; I guess it was hunting and there were many small birds very nearby on the ground and in the trees.  HABITAT: This bird was sitting on a lower dead branch, near a golf cart path, next to a very bushy area and low spot in the wash. This is a location well known to have many birds.  PLUMAGE:  Upper: Dark brown back with a few White patches (indicates immature) Under: Quite spectacular orange/white markings like scales on it’s breast.   Not an immature Red Tail (no dark brown belly streaks on white breast) Not an immature Harris Hawk(no strongly mottled white spots on dark brown breast)  Not an immature American Kestrel (no “squirrel monkey” face pattern; and eye is not black/brown)  Possibly an immature Coopers or Sharp-shinned.  SIZE: This hawk very small (blue jay size), less than 12”. (definitely not a Coopers, Red Tail or Harris).   UNDER PARTS: Has orange/white scales on it’s breast, like an immature Sharp Shinned.  (not “thin, chocolate brown streaks” like an immature Coopers).  EYE SIZE: Eye is relatively large compared to it’s head, like a Sharp Shinned.  (not smaller proportioned, like Coopers, color is orange/yellow not dark colored like a Kestrel)  EYE POSITION: Eye is closer to the centre of it’s head, like a Sharp Shinned.  (not close to beak, like a Coopers).   CROWN: No crown, the nape and crown are the same color, like a Sharp Shinned. (not a dark crown, like a Coopers).   TAIL FEATHERS: All the same length, like a Sharp Shinned. (not progressive lengths, with the centre feather longer, like a Coopers).  TAIL TIP: Brown tip on the tail, like a Sharp Shinned. (no obvious white tip, like a Coopers).  CONCLUSION: This is an immature Sharp-Shinned Hawk  - based on it's very small size, it is likely a male (Females are considerably larger than males) - based on it's plummage it likely 1st year. //benburtt.blogspot.com/2005/01/ntifying-coopers-and-sharp-shinned.html

A small bodied accipiter with a heavily streaked chest  and a barred square and white-tipped tail distinctively seen in a series of photos as it dispatched a BLJA. 22F NW winds, blue skies.  I saw many BLJA initially so I stopped at the Young's Mountain Road. The AMCR were on the ground when I realized there was a Sharp-shinned Hawk and it had just captured a BLJA. The struggle to dispatch the BAJA took about 8 to 10 minutes which I tried to capture below. The BLJA was fighting valiantly and was calling loudly initially. There was a mobbing of sorts going on initially which included some BLJA and AMCR. I changed position but kept a good distance away capturing unique moments. Finally the BLJA stopped fighting and the SSHA flew off just as I looked away briefly, it was gone. As I think about the entire event, the BLJA feathers flying on the wind is always the most stunning moment in the struggle. The SSHA dispatched the BLJA by going for its heart or disembowelment.

We initially saw it in the woods.  An hour later, as I was watching the intense bird activity at the feeders, that were full, the hawk (I assume it was the same) swooped in from behind me, flying low and landing at the base of a bush.  It was sudden and super fast, the hawk must have been perched on one of the tall trees surrounding the playground.  For a second I thought that it was another Blue Jays (there were a few pecking seeds on the ground), it was roughly the same size.  The hawk flew up again almost instantaneously, showing impressive acrobatic skills, and disappeared across the road, in direction of the boardwalk.  I didn't have the impression that it took any bird (there was no shrieking and no blood on the snow), but if it did, it was one of the titmice and chickadees hopping around in that spot.  It took a moment for the numerous birds around the feeders to see the danger and react.  By the time they scattered vocalizing in alarm, the hawk was gone.  After a short while, they went back to eat.

A sharp-shinned hawk appeared in our yard late this morning followed by a few blue jays.  Within a few minutes there were 7 blue jays and 3 black-billed magpies attempting to drive it from the area, something we've seen them do successfully several times this winter.  This time the hawk refused to leave, resulting in a sustained series of attacks and counter-attacks, with the sharpie initiating about a third of the attacks and the jays the rest.  The jays and magpies used the tangle of branches of shrubs and trees as a means of escape.  After about 20 minutes the magpies left the area, and 5 of the jays five minutes after that.  The two remaining jays continued alarm calls for another 5 minutes, then left the area.  The sharpie was then able to perch peacefully in a tree in our yard.  Unfortunately, its perseverance was unrewarded as the ruckus had alerted the usual feeder users.  Unseasonably cold weather (today's high temperature was 20 C colder than normal) is keeping feeders busy, and likely increasing the sharp-shinned hawk's need for more calories.  It is interesting to see these combined behaviours given that as recent as 2002, when Birds of Saskatoon was published, sharp-shinned hawks were considered 'irregular winter laggard(s, with only) three records'.  They are now somewhat common winter residents in some areas of Saskatoon.

Media notes: For a size comparison, the handrail is composed of a horz. 1" railing and a vert. 2x4 support for a total of 4 1/2-inches.  I don't know how to account for camera angle, parallax or the like but feel this shows the bird is a SSHA.
Observation Details: I labeled this as a SSHA for the following reasons:  1.  The streaks go almost down to the vent area.  On a COHA they should thin out on the belly.  2.  There is only a very narrow white terminal band on the tail. A COHA should be thicker.  3.  The tail is notched, not rounded like a COHA, (Discrepancy;,it could be missing tail feathers).  4.  The tarsus appears very thin to me, (but I don't have much experience judging that).  5. The size, in comparison to the 1" railing and 2x4 support board, indicates it is too small for a COHA. I think it could be either a rather large male or a mid-sized female SSHA.

Observation Details: Looked out window to see why the usual contingent of small birds were not at the feeders to see this bird perched in the dogwood.  Round, smallish head on broad shoulder, brownish back with some white feathers, squared tail, no broad white tip to tail, no dark cap nor light feathers extending to nape (although in some of the pictures there appears to be a cap, however this is a shadow of a tree branch), thin "pencil" legs, all characteristic of a young female Sharp-shinned Hawk.  Probably the same bird as two days ago coming back to hunt the small birds. This Kestrel-sized pair of hawks showed up here together this morning, then proceeded to only moderately agitate the larger birds that usually come for breakfast (Steller's Jays, Band-tailed Pigeons, etc.). Both SSHAs appeared to be current-year youths with small rounded heads, brown backs and wings, heavily streaked breasts, and bright yellow eyes.  One hawk actually tried to dive from a power line onto a Steller's Jay feeding on the ground ... only to be easily shaken off by the Jay!

Observation Details: When Dad woke me up at about 10:00, he told me that there was an accipiter with prey in our backyard. I jumped out of bed and came out to find this bird disemboweling what we eventually realized was a male cardinal. We got incredible views of this bird as it ripped apart its prey on the ground under the forsythia bush by the deck. I photographed it copiously, and eventually Dad and I got the scope and trained it on the hawk. This yielded a whole new dimension of amazing viewing. After some research, I identified the bird as a Sharp-shinned. (I feel pretty comfortable identifying flying accipiters, but I find perched birds like this one to be tricky). It seemed to have a small head with a relatively large eye. The bird was a juvenile; its chest markings extended relatively far down its belly, and were reddish and broad. Its tail appeared squared off, but its tip was very tattered. I got decent photographs from many angles. Two are below. (Note the foot of the poor cardinal, sitting to the right of the carcass.) The hawk finished eating at about 12:00, at which point it hopped up onto a very low forsythia branch and sat there digesting. The bird shifted position a few times, but it stayed under the forsythia bush until we went outside through the garage at about 12:30, at which point it took off and flew up into the large pines in the backyard.

Media notes: Perched and posibly resting after subduing the prey whihc was just a few feet belwo, still concealed by th esnow.
Observation Details: Probable female given it killed a Mourning dove.  First saw this bird on the ground with only its head and mantling wings above the snow.  It stayed there for several minutes, occasionally moving as the dove (which could not be seen beneath the snow at this point) apparently struggled.  The hawk then flew up to a tree branch only a few feet above the ground and may have been resting after the struggle.  It then dropped to the snow again and it became apparent that the dove was not yet dead as it flapped its wings as the hawk pulled it upward.  The hawk started to pluck the dove but decided to move to a more sheltered location.  It was barely able to fly and set down at the back of our yard, about 20 m away.  A minute later it carried the prey over a low fence and dropped down again amongst some sheltering trees.

Locality: Private Personal Residence, NE, St.Pete, FL
Observation Details: Sub-adult.  Perched in Oaks, flushed the moment I spotted it.   Photo shows the short wide body, and not the long tubular shape of a Cooper's Hawk.  Body has heavy coarse steaks and some barring, Sub-adult Cooper's has finer streaking on the body.    A shorter squared tail  because the feathers are all the same length. Cooper's would show a longer tail with uneven feather length giving it a rounded look.    I do not see young Sharpies often in Pinellas, mostly adults.    In fact I believe this is only my second photo of  a sub-adult.

Exact count of migrants.  One of the largest SSHA flights most New England hawkwatchers have ever seen. Today's total exceeded all seasonal totals going back through the Hawkcount records (2006) and perhaps one of the largest Spring Sharpie flights in MA history.  This is an all-time high single day count at the Plum Island hawkwatch site for Sharp-shinned Hawk.  Sharpies started streaming over in the gentle SW winds at 8am EDT and as the SW winds increased, the pace of the migration quickened. Our count reached approximately 400 Sharpies before Noon EDT and the wind direction went slightly N to NW, changing the pace from 'historic' to 'excellent.'   At times, we had groups of up to 10 Sharpies naked eye visible going overhead.  We worked carefully and conservatively to avoid overcounting and double-counting with our experienced team of volunteer  hawkwatchers.  The count lasted until 6pm EDT when the final migrants streamed through.

Observation Details: At least two individuals present, possibly three. First found an adult male perched high in a bare pine, and took some photos of it. Eventually it flew off and possibly landed nearby, because a little later I heard calls from the general area in which it disappeared. When I looked up, I saw another individual fly over high, also a male; presumably the perched individual also saw this bird fly over, and that's why it called. About an hour later, I found a subadult male being harassed by a group of seven Steller's Jays. The jays would fly up to it and land in the same tree, all the while screaming. The hawk on several occasions would chase off a jay, either because it was annoyed by the taunting jays or because it thought it would be able to catch one.

Media notes: This is the first individual, which appears to be clean white below, with a very faint orange wash on the flanks.

From inside the house I saw this bird make a strafing run down the length of the backyard juniper hedge. I went outside and spotted the bird perched on the fence on the east side of the yard. I went back into the house to grab my camera and gradually began to approach the bird. It was so intent on potential prey that it allowed me to get within 20’. It stayed on the fence until I was satisfied as far as photos went. It disappeared while I was busy filling the birds feeders. While doing so I heard agitated vocalizations from House Sparrows in the hedge, as well as rustling noises. This was followed by an exodus of HOSP from the hedge. I waited for the SSHA to emerge in pursuit, but I did not see it, so I finished up my feeder filling task. When done, as I walked toward the back door, I saw the SSHA on the ground next to the hedge, standing in a pile of feathers. I was able to observe and photograph the bird from inside the house as it fed for an extended period. The SSHA eventually flew to an oak tree where it continued its meal. I went out to obtain additional photos. When the bird moved to a higher perch I went inside. This was the most prolonged encounter with this species in the yard (where its an annual winter visitor), or anywhere for that matter. It was the most confiding (or distracted/innocent/hungry) individual by far. No bigger than a BLJA, so presumably a male.

Locality: Sleeping Bears Dunes NL--D.H. Day CG
Observation Details: After six years of birding a Sharpie finally sat still for a portrait!  My birding partner at first thought she had seen a Blue Jay as we drove by.  We stopped and found this hawk. The far away pic is not cropped, shot with a 400 mm lens from across the road.  Size:  This is a small bird, about the size of large Blue Jay or Mourning Dove.  Body:  Though looking a bit chubby for a Sharpie, it was sort of hunkered down giving it the barrel shape look of a Coopers Hawk.  Color: The nape and back were distinctly the same gray color pattern.  Legs and Feet:  The legs are hidden but the foot showing is thin in comparison to the Coopers.  Tail:  The true length is hidden because of the angle of view but lacks the distinct bold white tip of the Coopers. Flight:  The observed flight was away from us and brief.  The wings were short but wide and the flight pattern was  to flap it's wings a few times then glide, then repeat as it headed for more dense forest. Overall, because of the size and flight characteristics we conclude that this is a Sharp-shinned Hawk.

Tiny hawk killed a White-Winged Dove in our yard! We did not see the dove before we saw the hawk eating it. After 10 minutes a congress of crows was attracted: heard at least 3 crows calling from nearby trees. Soon that was too much for the hawk, who flew off with its prey. Hawk definitely Sharp-Shinned, not Cooper's.  Hawk was the same size as the dove (~12"), had solid gray nape with continuous color from crown to back, and short barred tail with squared tips. Please see photos; particularly, please note the photo where the hawk is bending low over the dove when the crows were calling, as if to hide the prey from the crows.
